Predicting Hospital Readmission using Machine Learning and Accessing Model Discrimination by Gender and Race

Hospitals often suffer from crowding and must allocate beds and resources to patients most in need [1]. A patient who is deemed to no longer require hospital care, can be discharged safely. However, hospitals often discharge patients who eventually are readmitted in a short time period. This might have negative consequences since we wrong in discharging them early.

In this project we attempt to predict whether a patient will be re-admitted to a hospital within a month. Such a model can be used to triage which patients should be discharged by their likelihood of re-admission. Moreover, we need to ensure and assess that this model performs equally well across different demographic groups. Previous work has shown that machine learning (ML) based algorithms are discriminatory in healthcare [2].

Data: We use publicly available data from diabetic patients from 130-US hospitals for years 1999-2008 [3]. This data can be publicly downloaded from 1. This data contains data from over 100k patients with several characteristics for each patient including age, gender, lab measurements and more. The label for each patient is whether they were admitted within 30 days or not. However, this data is not clean: many rows have missing features, missing labels, columns are badly formatted, we have mixture of categorical and numerical data, and categorical features have over 600 distinct values. Figure 1 below shows the percentage of missing values for the features in our dataset, we have 6 features with noticeable missingness, the rest have no missing values

Approach: Approach: Our first step is to clean this dataset to make it ready for our machine learning models to learn on. We will impute missing values, recode values appropriately (numeric vs factor), remove columns that are uninformative and more. After that, we will split our dataset into 3 parts: training, validation and testing. We do this so that we can evaluate our model appropriately. After that, we learn different kinds of machine learning models on the training dataset and evaluate their performance with respect to the area under the receiving operating curve. We do this because the label distribution is uneven, in Figure 2 we show how many patients are readmitted within 30 days, notice that is it between 25%. Accuracy will not be as reliable measure of performance, especially since we want to rank patients for Triage. After picking the best model on the validation set, we measure it’s performance on the test. We then measure it’s performance by the subgroups of gender and race. We do this by computing confidence intervals for the AUC for each group and comparing them

Results

Data Cleaning and Preparation

As we mentioned in the introduction, our dataset is messy and needs to be cleaned. We outline here all the steps we did to make our dataset ready for machine learning training and show our results.

Step 1: Removing rows with no labels. For more than 50% of points in our dataset, there is no record of re-admission of the patient, therefore we remove all these rows. We are left with 46902 patients. Note that we cannot impute the label as this would create bias in the dataset.

Step 2: Removing and Imputing Features with missingness. In Figure 1 we showed the features with missing values. For the feature ‘weight’ more than 80% of rows are missing values, thus we remove it completely. The remaining 5 features with missing values are all categorical, thus we replace the missing value with the most commonly occurring element. Note we cannot define an average or median over categorical values, thus the most common value is the best way.

Step 3: Removing uninformative features. For each of the categorical variables in our dataset, we obtain the number of unique values for each column. We first note that we have 4 columns with a single unique value: meaning the column is always the same. Therefore, we remove these 4 features. Second, we have for each patient their ID, however, all patients are distinct, thus we remove the patient ID. Finally, we have three variables for diagnosis codes: diag_1: primary diagnosis, diag_2: secondary diagnosis, diag_3: secondary diagnosis (additional). The third diagnosis is often redundant thus we remove it.

Step 4: Recoding categorical variables. The diagnosis features (diag_1 and diag_2) have 616 unique values each. These two alone would lead to 1230 features in our models. This is clearly too many features and we run the risk of overfitting. What we do instead is find the most common 50 diagnosis codes, and if a patient has a primary or secondary diagnosis code in those 50, we keep that value, otherwise, we code it as ‘other’.

In addition to that, even numeric features in our dataset are coded as characters, thus we code everything appropriately to either numeric or factor appropriately. As a list filtering step, we look at correlations between features, however, we do not see any features that are redundant at the end of these 4 steps. Figure 3 shows this correlation between features.

Step 5: Data splitting and initial feature selection. We split our dataset into a training set (70%), validation set (10%) and test set (20%). This gives 32832, 4686 and 9384 points respectively. To try to filter more features, we see how predictive each feature alone is at predicting readmission from just the training data. We get the results in Figure 4, this does not allow us to eliminate any clear feature (all above 0.5), but some are not statistically different from 0.5.

Model Training

Using the split datasets from above, we are ready to train our machine learning models.

We experiment with a logistic regression baseline and a random forest model. We train both on our training data and evaluate their performance initially on our validation data. The results are in Table 1. We can see that the random forest model performs better than logistic regression baseline and has non-trivial performance. Thus we will use this random forest model going forward. Note we can improve performance by doing hyperparameter validation, but we leave this to future work.

Model Accuracy AUC
Logistic Regression 0.758 0.593
Random Forrest 0.761 0.609

Model Evaluation by Race and Gender

We are now ready to touch the test set and evaluate our model on it.

We obtain an AUC of 0.600 with a 90% confidence interval of [0.5873,0.6101] using the DeLong methods [4]. Before we evaluate the performance on the subgroups we are interested in, it is important to understand how many samples we have from each group. We plot the distribution of the population in each subgroup before data imputation in Figure 5. This will be very helpful in explaining our results in a second.

We plot in Figure 6, the AUC of the RF model on each of the subgroups. We first notice that the model performs slightly better on women than men. This can be partially explained because we have more data from women than we have for men (see Figure 5). In terms of race, we see that we have very large CI for all races except Caucasian and African American, this because of the limited data from these races. However, we notice that the performance on Caucasian is higher than that of African Americans. Another reason is that of unequal data from each group, since the model is trained to minimize average error, it will tend to do better on majority groups.

Conclusion

In this project, we studied the problem of predicting diabetic patient readmission from hospital data. We first had to do significant data wrangling to make sure our dataset was clean and we are able to train models from it. We performed data imputation, feature selection and feature cleaning. We then learned different models including linear and random forest models to predict patient readmission. We used data splitting and AUC to evaluate our model performance since we had class imbalance. Our results showed that the random forest model performed best and had a non-trivial performance of 0.6 AUC. We then evaluated the performance of our model on the different subgroups in the dataset. Our results revealed a noticeable but not statistically significant gap between the model’s performance on women vs men and white vs African American. We explained that this gap might have occurred because of the unequal data sizes for each sub-group.

Future Work:

While our model’s performance was non-trivial, it is not as high as I would have hoped. I can improv the models performance by doing better hyperparameter tuning and training other types of models. One interesting direction if the rows with missing labels can still be leveraged to improv prediction using unsupervised learning.

While our work revealed some gap between the model performance on subgroups, we did not study how to address it in our work. One possible directions is to train models with explicit performance across different subgroups using fair machine learning and the fairml package [5].

plot_prop <- function(df, col, label){
  df %>%
    group_by(!!sym(col)) %>%
    summarise(prop = mean(!!sym(label))) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = !!sym(col), y = prop)) +
    geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
    labs(x = col, y = "Proportion of label being 1")
}

Different Models

linear <- glm(readmitted ~ ., data = train_data, family = 'binomial')
linear_pred <- predict(linear, newdata = val_data, type = "response")
linear_auc <- auc(val_data$readmitted, linear_pred)
## Setting levels: control = 0, case = 1
## Setting direction: controls < cases
linear_acc <- mean(val_data$readmitted == round(linear_pred))
print(linear_acc)
## [1] 0.7577892
print(linear_auc)
## Area under the curve: 0.5933
rf <- randomForest(readmitted ~ ., data = train_data, probability = TRUE)
rf_pred <- predict(rf, newdata = val_data,  type = "prob")[,2]
rf_auc <- auc(val_data$readmitted, rf_pred)
## Setting levels: control = 0, case = 1
## Setting direction: controls < cases
rf_acc <- mean(val_data$readmitted == round(rf_pred))
print(rf_auc)
## Area under the curve: 0.6091
print(rf_acc)
## [1] 0.761417

RF is better, so we will use it as our final model
